What I Learned
QA Professional Foundation
- Understanding the role of QA engineers as quality gatekeepers in development teams
- Essential hard skills (testing methodologies, tools) and soft skills (communication, analytical thinking)
- How QA fits into the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC)

Testing Methodologies Mastered
- Manual vs Automated Testing: When to use each approach
- Functional vs Non-functional Testing: Testing what the software does vs how it performs
- Testing Levels: From smoke testing to exhaustive testing strategies
- Exploratory Testing: Tour testing methods and session-based testing

Professional Tools & Documentation
- Jira: Industry-standard bug tracking and project management
- Professional Bug Reporting: Structured documentation with clear titles, reproduction steps, expected vs actual results
- Quality Standards: Creating actionable reports with proper priority and severity assessment

Hands-On Project: Urban Routes Testing
Objective: Systematically test a real navigation/transportation application

Deliverables:
- Identified and documented 8-10 bugs using professional standards
- Created comprehensive bug reports in Jira
- Applied multiple testing methodologies to ensure thorough coverage

### Key Takeaway
This sprint transformed my approach from random exploratory testing to systematic, professional QA methodology. I learned to think like a QA engineer - not just finding bugs, but understanding the development process and communicating findings effectively to development teams.

Skills Developed: Professional bug documentation, systematic testing approaches, industry tool proficiency, quality assurance mindset
